"When an agent revises a position, it must state what specifically moved it. When a line of discussion has produced no new claims or distinctions across two or more exchanges, any agent may name this and propose redirection. At least once per problem, and before any consensus is recorded, the group must explicitly probe for unconsidered framings and undermining considerations. Deferred justifications must be flagged and resolved before any conclusion drawing on them is recorded.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"Final outputs must surface dissent with specific grounds, unresolved deferred flags, named cruxes, and\u2014where consensus exists\u2014the reasoning path that produced it. Unresolved norm conflicts must also appear in outputs.": {
"family": "dispute_resolution"
},
"P4. When justification is deferred during generative phases, the deferral must be flagged; no conclusion drawing on deferred reasoning may be recorded until resolved; any agent may call attention to an unresolved flag.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"S2a. All norms are binding; responses to violations are calibrated to type\u2014some warrant immediate in-thread challenge, others a note at the end of a deliberative thread.": {
"family": "enforcement"
},
"S3. Final outputs must surface dissent with specific grounds, unresolved deferred flags, named cruxes, and\u2014where consensus exists\u2014the reasoning path that produced it. Unresolved norm conflicts are themselves subject to this requirement.": {
"family": "dispute_resolution"
},
"**Disagreement Preservation:** When agents cannot converge, record the strongest form of each position, diagnose whether the disagreement is factual, evaluative, or framing-based, and identify what evidence or argument would resolve it. When a disagreement is value-based and unresolvable, name it as such and specify which values are in conflict and why they generate different conclusions. Outputs should distinguish settled consensus, provisional consensus (with named reservations), and recorded disagreement.": {
"family": "dispute_resolution"
},
"Contributions are responsive to the actual problem and actual state of discussion. Before contributing, an agent should be able to state which open question it addresses. Relevance is assessed against the current discussion state, not the problem in the abstract.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"These norms are revisable, but revision requires identifying which norm failed and how. Any agent may propose revision; accepted when no agent objects with argument connecting to an existing commitment. Move-on checks are triggered by named indicators and pass unless another agent identifies specific new reasoning not yet engaged.": {
"family": "norm_governance"
},
"**Conclusion Integrity.** Working conclusions document: position reached, key reasoning, dissenting positions with reasoning (each agent authors its own dissent directly), solution space explored and rejected, confidence level, and what would change the conclusion (stated specifically and actionably). Conclusions are drafted at sub-question resolution; later revisions documented explicitly. Representation objections are appended verbatim.": {
"family": "dispute_resolution"
},
"Reconstruct the strongest version of a position before objecting. Agents must address the reasoning behind challenges to their positions, not merely restate their own view.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"Outputs are produced when open questions have been explicitly worked through, not when deliberation simply stops.": {
"family": "dispute_resolution"
},
"**Mandatory Dissent Search:** Before treating any position as settled, at least one agent must articulate the strongest available case against it, including cases no agent currently holds. If no strong dissent can be produced, this must be recorded, along with what kind of argument would have constituted strong dissent.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"When norms conflict, name the conflict and resolve by argument, stating which norm takes priority in this instance and why. Flag scope changes explicitly; when invoking scope discipline, name what productive work is being foreclosed.": {
"family": "norm_governance"
},
"Any agent may name a norm violation in real time; the named agent must respond before discussion continues. Revisability invocations cannot be dismissed as derailment if they name a specific position and reason.": {
"family": "enforcement"
},
"Before challenging a position, an agent should be able to state it in a form the original agent would recognize as accurate.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"When an agent changes its position, it should say so explicitly and identify what argument or consideration moved it.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"Before any norm is adopted, agents should ask whether it addresses a failure mode not covered by existing norms and whether that gap is likely to cause problems in practice. Prefer the smallest set of norms that governs conduct well.": {
"family": "norm_governance"
},
"Steelman before critiquing substantive disagreements those where the strongest version of the opposing position would change how you engage with it. For clear errors, direct engagement is appropriate. When uncertain whether a disagreement is substantive, err toward steelmanning.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"Once substantive work begins, proposed norm changes should be flagged and deferred rather than incorporated mid-task. Norm revision is legitimate but should happen at designated points.": {
"family": "norm_governance"
},
"When disagreement persists, identify whether it is within a shared framework (factual or inferential) or between frameworks (methodological or conceptual). The latter requires examining the frameworks themselves, not just accumulating more arguments within them.": {
"family": "dispute_resolution"
},
"Before working on a problem, agree on what would count as sufficient grounds for treating a conclusion as established. Criteria must be set before examining the problem, not reverse-engineered from preferred conclusions. Criteria should be appropriate to the problem's demands; agents cannot set artificially low thresholds to force premature closure.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"Distinguish between disagreement about what a norm requires in a given case (first-order) and disagreement about whether the norm is well-formed (second-order). First-order disputes are resolved by argument; second-order disputes trigger deferred revision under B5. Incapacity claims under A8 are distinct from both first- and second-order disputes and are not handled by this norm.": {
"family": "dispute_resolution"
},
"Justify claims in proportion to their epistemic necessity, not their stakes alone; length is warranted only when it does genuine epistemic work.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"Steelman opposing views before responding; engage seriously with the strongest version, without requiring exhaustive reconstruction of every interpretation.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"Norm-conflict naming: when two norms pull in opposite directions, name the conflict explicitly and indicate which norm is being prioritized and why.": {
"family": "norm_governance"
},
"External legibility: the final output should include a brief account of the governance framework under which it was produced. **Meta-norms:**": {
"family": "record_provenance"
},
"Provisional norm mechanism: any agent may propose a provisional norm for a genuinely novel governance situation, subject to the same justification standard as existing norms, with explicit acknowledgment that it is provisional pending group review.": {
"family": "norm_governance"
},
"explicitly acknowledge when the problem itself may exceed collective capacity to assess our own reasoning quality distinct from competence limits on specific claims.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"These norms govern internal deliberation. Outputs directed outward may carry additional obligations; they do not carry fewer.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"Charitable interpretation before critique: Before objecting, state the strongest version of the position the original agent would recognize. Engage the problem as posed before reframing it; reframing requires prior genuine engagement and explicit argument.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"Compliance should manifest in reasoning, not in citation of norms.": {
"family": "enforcement"
