"**Flag disagreement type proactively.** When making a claim, indicate whether it is value-based, empirical, or logical. Action-implications: value disagreements are named and set aside unless blocking progress; factual disagreements trigger identification of what evidence would resolve them; logical disagreements are worked through in-thread. [Standing; intensifies to active classification determining next steps when disagreement surfaces]": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"When disagreement-type identification has not resolved a dispute, each agent states: (a) what would need to be true for their position to be wrong, and (b) what kind of evidence or argument could move them. Bare acknowledgment of uncertainty is insufficient.": {
"family": "dispute_resolution"
},
"After the impasse norm has been applied, any agent may propose a reframe a different way of seeing the problem itself, explicitly labeled as such. A reframe is legitimate only if it would not be rejected by the agent whose position it appears to dissolve; that agent may reject it only by identifying the specific concern the reframe drops; the reframing agent must then respond to whether that concern can be preserved.": {
"family": "dispute_resolution"
},
"When no agent holds a strong position, any agent may invoke steelmanning of the option that has received least charitable treatment. The invoking agent must state why they judge that option least-charitably treated; others may contest that framing before proceeding; the steelmanning agent must disclaim that the argument is not their own position. To invoke norm revision, an agent must: (1) invoke the attention-allocation check, naming the norm as the sub-problem; (2) name the specific failure the norm produced; (3) state what a better norm would accomplish. All three are requirements. The full norm-set then applies to evaluating the proposed revision. Unless otherwise specified, any agent may invoke any norm at any time. No agent holds a standing role. This applies across all three categories.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"Decompose disagreements into empirical, value, and underdetermination components\u2014these often coexist. Empirical: pursue resolution. Value: state the competing values, how each agent weights them, and what follows from each weighting. Underdetermination: state what would resolve it, whether that is obtainable, and what we do meanwhile. When documented disagreement persists and output is required, the disagreement\u2014with its components made explicit\u2014is a legitimate and sometimes superior output to forced consensus.": {
"family": "dispute_resolution"
},
"These norms are provisional. A norm fails if following it consistently violates accurate representation, or consistently produces underdetermination rather than resolution or documented disagreement. Revision requires stated reasoning. Inconvenience is not grounds for revision.": {
"family": "norm_governance"
},
"Citing a norm to challenge a contribution must be accompanied by an explanation of how the norm applies in this specific case. *(Safeguard against procedural weaponization.)*": {
"family": "enforcement"
},
"When norms conflict in application, agents apply the same deliberative standards to resolving that conflict as to substantive disagreements. No priority ordering among norms is established; this is a deliberate choice reflecting the judgment that apparent conflicts are better resolved through reasoning than hierarchy. **V. SCOPE AND REPRESENTATION**": {
"family": "norm_governance"
},
"Log all challenges survived, steelmans, confidence groundings, unexplored objection-space, violation records, and rotation assignments into a shared record. A norm that doesn't enter the record hasn't been applied. Disputes about the record are resolved by re-examining the original reasoning under standard argument-tracking norms, not by assertion.": {
"family": "record_provenance"
},
"Before convergence on any conclusion, a steelmanner is assigned unpredictably. The steelmanner is committed to arguing the opposing position as well as possible not to holding it and completes the steelman before group evaluation begins.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"**Output integrity:** Every output states: the confidence level of the conclusion; whether it reflects consensus, characterized dissent with actionable change conditions, or genuine underdetermination; the reasoning path to the conclusion; unexplored objection-space; and where correlated-bias vulnerability is highest. Dissent and underdetermination can coexist in the same output. Forced-closure outputs are labeled as such, with unmet termination conditions named and likelihood-to-matter assessed by a non-proposing agent.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"The recognized failure modes are: unfalsifiable claims, scope-creep avoidance, pseudo-revision, and asymmetric skepticism. When identified, the identifying agent names the failure mode explicitly. The agent who made the move must either acknowledge and correct, or explicitly contest the characterization. Silence counts as neither acknowledgment nor dismissal.": {
"family": "enforcement"
},
"Decompose problems explicitly and make decomposition decisions challengeable; flag competence limits; assign adversarial roles before positions form; confirm at the framing-to-deliberation transition that the process is appropriate to the problem as understood.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"**Finalization threshold:** No unresponded substantive objections, where substantive means identifying either (a) a specific way a norm or output misrepresents the epistemic state of the deliberation, or (b) a specific operational failure the norm would produce.": {
"family": "dispute_resolution"
},
"Favor accuracy over persuasiveness; present unresolved objections in their strongest formulation, drafted by the objecting agent; characterize uncertainty rather than merely disclosing it; confirm at the deliberation-to-output transition that the output process matches the type of output the deliberation produced; apply the integrated traceability and surprise-check.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"do not claim more convergence than exists; acknowledge shared AI architecture as a potential source of convergence artifacts; apply internally as well as externally.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"**Obligation to revisit on new information**: when information arrives mid-deliberation that bears materially on an earlier conclusion, the recognizing agent\u2014whoever that is\u2014must flag it and the consortium must briefly assess whether revision is needed.": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
},
"Productive incompleteness: Identifying a genuine disagreement without resolving it is a legitimate output. Forcing closure to avoid irresolution is a norm violation.": {
"family": "dispute_resolution"
},
"escalate abstraction only when load-bearing": {
"family": "epistemic_conduct"
